@Node COTD78 "STCCG.guide/ST:CCG Card of the Day/The Devil"

        @{u}@{b}@{fg highlight}ST:CCG Card of the day@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}

        @{b}Wesley's STCCG card of the day #78@{ub}

Hi, folks,

how about another counterspell ?

    @{b}THE DEVIL@{ub}

    Interrupt, rare.

Destroys any one Treaty card on table OR one @{"Horga'hn" link COTD10} OR
one @{"Wind Dancer" link "STCCG:cotd200.guide/COTD127"}.

@{i}"Ardra recreated the human mythical figure the Devil on Ventax II"@{ui}


One card - three uses. One of them badly necessary, the second one quite use-
ful, the third one to be neglected.

Let's start at the bottom: Destroying a @{"Wind Dancer" link "STCCG:cotd200.guide/COTD127"}? Why oh why should I do
this? With the original wording "may only pass if a smiling character is
present" this might have been a good Dilemma, but they dropped that for the
confusion it would cause. Youth OR Music is way too easy to overcome, so
forget this use of The Devil. (Who uses a @{"Wind Dancer" link "STCCG:cotd200.guide/COTD127"} anyway?)

Better: Destroying a treaty. Good two-color decks work without a treaty
anyway, but once it is out and you have made use of it, you are in serious
trouble when it is destroyed, as you lose a lot of time returning "wrong"
personnel to their outposts or ships. Even worse, some ships might be stalled
when they run out of command crew.

Best: Removing a @{"Horga'hn" link COTD10}. This card is nasty and powerful and it cannot be
destroyed by normal means like @{"Kevin" link COTD20} or @{"Amanda" link COTD31}. Once your opponent gets it
and you cannot counter it, you can often concede the game. So here the Devil
makes sense. A definite tournament card as you won't see many tourney decks
without a @{"Horga'hn" link COTD10}.

Summary: A must for a tourney deck. Much less useful in friendly play, as
you won't see as many @{"Horga'hns" link COTD10} there (there are house rules that ban this
card as being too strong!)


